Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for the Next.js project.

## Changes Made:

### Package Installation:
- Installed `@vercel/analytics` (v2.0.1) using npm
- Updated `package.json` with the new dependency
- Updated `package-lock.json` with dependency tree

### Code Configuration:
Modified `app/layout.tsx`:
- Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next"`
- Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag, after the closing `</AuthProvider>` tag

## Implementation Details:

The project uses:
- Framework: Next.js 16.2.2 with App Router
- Package Manager: npm (package-lock.json detected)
- TypeScript: Enabled

Following the official Vercel documentation (https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart), I:
1. Fetched the latest installation instructions directly from Vercel's documentation
2. Identified this as a Next.js App Router project based on the presence of `app/layout.tsx`
3. Applied the framework-specific instructions for Next.js App Router
4. Placed the `<Analytics />` component at the end of the body tag as recommended

## Verification:

✅ Build completed successfully with `npm run build`
✅ TypeScript compilation passed
✅ All routes generated properly (16/16 pages)
✅ No new linting errors introduced by the changes
✅ Lock file updated correctly

## Next Steps:

To enable analytics on Vercel:
1. Deploy this project to Vercel
2. Navigate to the Analytics tab in your Vercel dashboard
3. Click "Enable" to activate Web Analytics for your project
4. Analytics will start tracking page views automatically

The Analytics component will automatically track page views and send data to Vercel once enabled in the dashboard.
